The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Business Briefs

 New Delhi, Sept. 20: The rapid economic growth in India and China has reduced the global income inequality, the World Bank said today. ?Global income inequality has steadily increased over the long run until the onset of rapid economic growth in China and India in the 1980s,? said the World Development Report 2006, released by the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD). If China and India are excluded, the gap has widened among the rich and poorer nations, the report titled Equity and Development said.

 Vienna, Sept. 20: Opec today offered up every last barrel of its spare production in a bid to reassure consumer countries about energy supply security. The cartel is putting its remaining 2 million barrels a day of crude on the block for world oil markets from October 1 for a period of three months, provided there is a demand. Opec will maintain its official production at 28 million BPD, a spokesperson said.

 New Delhi, Sept. 20: The new duty neutralisation scheme to replace the duty entitlement passbook scheme (DEPB) is likely to be unveiled next month. The cabinet is expected to take up the proposal by the middle of October, sources said.

 Mumbai, Sept. 20: Gold continued to attract heavy stockists? buying in line with the steep rally in global prices today. Standard gold shot up by Rs 95 to end at a 10-month high of Rs 6,705 on the bullion market.

 New Delhi, Sept. 20: The company law board today adjourned till December 8 the hearing in a case related to the alleged oppression and mismanagement in MP Birla flagship Birla Corp.

 New Delhi, Sept. 20: Cairn Energy has raised its estimates of oil reserves in the Rajasthan oilfield to 1.7 billion barrels, which is more than 50 per cent higher than the previous one.

 Coonoor, Sept. 20: The Tea Board is likely to be reconstituted soon, said Union minister of state for commerce and industry E.V.K.S. Elangovan.




